# Results – Simple World Implementation

This folder contains example outputs generated by the Simple World Implementation pipeline.  
Each result illustrates one or more stages of the classical computer vision processing: preprocessing, edge detection, line classification, figure–ground separation, and simple world coordinate mapping.

---

## 1. Example Image: simple_world_1.png

Files:

- `simple_world_1_original.png`  
  - Copy of the input Simple World scene used as the starting point.

- `simple_world_1_gray.png`  
  - Grayscale version of the original image, used for all further processing.

- `simple_world_1_edges.png`  
  - Canny edge map showing the main boundaries of the blocks as white edges on a black background.

- `simple_world_1_lines.png`  
  - Original image with detected line segments overlaid.  
  - Green lines mark vertical edges; red lines mark horizontal edges.

- `simple_world_1_figure_mask.png`  
  - Binary figure/ground mask.  
  - White pixels correspond to the block structure; black pixels correspond to background.

- `simple_world_1_figure_only.png`  
  - Original image with the mask applied so that only the blocks (figure) remain; the background is removed.

- `simple_world_1_world_coordinates.png`  
  - Multi‑panel figure including:
    - Original image  
    - Detected edges  
    - Edge classification (green vertical / red horizontal)  
    - X world coordinate map (intensity increases left to right)  
    - Y world coordinate map (intensity increases top to bottom)  
    - Z world coordinate map (flat depth visualized with a colorbar)

- `simple_world_1_3d_surface.png`  
  - 3D surface plot generated from the X, Y, and Z coordinate maps.  
  - In the current implementation Z is constant, so the surface is a flat plane; this can be extended to different depths per block in future work.

